      <block class="full_text">
        <p>THE BRECHT MEMOIR By Eric Bentley. Northwestern University, cloth, $19.95; paper, $9.95.</p>
        <p>"From the outset," says the drama critic Eric Bentley about Bertolt Brecht, "our relationship had been founded on misunderstandings, and if from time to time it changed, the change was from one misunderstanding to another." "The Brecht Memoir," originally published in 1985, consists of anecdotes and letters chronicling events in the relationship of the two men. The 25-year-old Mr. Bentley met Brecht in 1942, when the German playwright was 43. There are tales here of Brecht and his wife, the actress Helene Weigel, and his mistress, Ruth Berlau, as well as colorful encounters with Brecht's artistic collaborators. There are two significant additions to this new edition: a brief foreword by the theater scholar Martin Esslin and an autobiographical postscript from Mr. Bentley.</p>
      </block>
